ZEsarUX (ZX Spectrum Next / tbblue) - NextBASIC host-disk LOAD/SAVE
===================================================================

What it does
    On the ZX Spectrum Next machine (--machine tbblue, NextZXOS/NextBASIC),
    makes the BASIC commands SAVE / LOAD / MERGE / ERASE with a plain
    filename (no drive letter, no path, no extension) operate directly on
    files in a host directory:

        SAVE "lib"   -> writes <hostdir>/lib.bas
        LOAD "game"  -> reads  <hostdir>/game.bas
        MERGE "lib"  -> merges <hostdir>/lib.bas
        SAVE "@"     -> re-saves to the last file opened through the handler
        ERASE "lib"  -> deletes <hostdir>/lib.bas

    Host .bas files are PLAIN TEXT BASIC LISTINGS - one numbered line per
    text line, exactly like the output of LIST - so they can be edited and
    versioned host-side with any editor. SAVE detokenizes the program to
    text; LOAD tokenizes it back (classic 48K keyword set, including the
    hidden 0Eh five-byte number forms; BIN literals are encoded as binary).
    Legacy raw tokenized files (first byte 0) are still accepted on LOAD.

    Non-ASCII ZX characters are preserved in the listings (UTF-8):

        block graphics 80h-8Fh   Unicode quadrant characters (the empty
                                 block 80h, which has no glyph, is \..)
        UDGs A-U (90h-A4h)       \a .. \u          (zmakebas convention)
        pound 60h / (c) 7Fh      UTF-8 pound and copyright signs
        anything else            \xHH               (lossless fallback)

    LOAD additionally accepts zmakebas-style block escapes (backslash plus
    two column characters from . ' , : meaning none/top/bottom/both, left
    column first - e.g. \': is the 8Bh block).
    The 128-byte PLUS3DOS header never touches the host: it is synthesized
    on LOAD and stripped on SAVE, and the variables area is stripped too.
    Saves are atomic (temp file + rename) and filename matching against the
    host directory is case-insensitive.

    (SAVE "" cannot be used for re-saving: the NextBASIC ROM rejects the
    empty filename with "Invalid file name" before it ever reaches the
    +3DOS layer, which is where this patch lives. Hence the "@" alias.)

    Filespecs containing ':', '/', '\', '.' or wildcards are passed through
    untouched to the real NextZXOS, so the OS still boots and runs from its
    SD image (tbblue.mmc) - only plain-name BASIC file access is hijacked.

How it works
    NextBASIC performs all its file access through the +3DOS-compatible API
    in ROM 2 (DOS_OPEN 0106h, DOS_CLOSE 0109h, DOS_READ 0112h, ...). The
    patch traps the jump-table entries when the TBBlue runs in +3e mode
    with the DOS ROM paged at 0000h-3FFFh, and services the calls from the
    host directory instead.

Activation
    Inert unless the environment variable ZESARUX_NEXTBASIC_DIR is set:

        ZESARUX_NEXTBASIC_DIR=$HOME/programs \
        zesarux --machine tbblue --mmc-file tbblue.mmc \
                --enable-mmc --enable-divmmc-ports

    Optionally, ZESARUX_NEXTBASIC_AUTOLOAD=<name> boots straight into
    <hostdir>/<name>.bas: the handler serves a synthetic
    c:/nextzxos/autoexec.bas ("10 LOAD "<name>"") and gives the loaded
    program an autostart line, so it LOADs and RUNs unattended.
    ZESARUX_NEXTBASIC_AUTOLOAD=- serves an empty autoexec instead, which
    suppresses any real autoexec on the SD image and boots to the NextZXOS
    menu.

    Requires the normal Spectrum core (the default); the reduced core
    (--spectrum-reduced-core) does not run these traps.

How to apply (against https://github.com/chernandezba/zesarux master)
    cd zesarux
    git apply /path/to/zesarux-nextbasic-hostdisk.patch

    Then build as usual, e.g.:
    cd src && ./configure && make

Verified
    Against ZEsarUX master 7d33f6b (13.1-SN, July 2026) with the bundled
    tbblue.mmc (NextZXOS 2.06H): SAVE producing text listings, LOAD/LIST/
    RUN of text listings, MERGE, ERASE, SAVE "@", autoload boot, and
    untouched NextZXOS boot/Browser access.

